# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: system-in-package
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] A **ball grid array** (**BGA**) is a type of surface-mount packaging (a chip carrier) used for integrated circuits.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] BGA packages are used to permanently mount devices such as microprocessors.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] A BGA can provide more interconnection pins than can be put on a dual in-line or flat package.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] The whole bottom surface of the device can be used, instead of just the perimeter.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] The traces connecting the package's leads to the wires or balls which connect the die to package are also on average shorter than with a perimeter-only type, leading to better performance at high speeds.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Soldering of BGA devices requires precise control and is usually done by automated processes such as in computer-controlled automatic reflow ovens.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] The BGA is descended from the pin grid array (PGA), which is a package with one face covered (or partly covered) with pins in a grid pattern which, in operation, conduct electrical signals between the integrated circuit and the printed circuit board (PCB) on which it is placed.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] In a BGA, the pins are replaced by pads on the bottom of the package, each initially with a tiny solder ball stuck to it.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] These solder spheres can be placed manually or by automated equipment, and are held in place with a tacky flux.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] The device is placed on a PCB with copper pads in a pattern that matches the solder balls.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] The assembly is then heated, either in a reflow oven or by an infrared heater, melting the balls.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Surface tension causes the molten solder to hold the package in alignment with the circuit board, at the correct separation distance, while the solder cools and solidifies, forming soldered connections between the device and the PCB.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] In more advanced technologies, solder balls may be used on both the PCB and the package.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Also, in stacked multi-chip modules, solder balls are used to connect two packages in a "package on package" configuration.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] The BGA addresses the problem of producing a miniature package for an integrated circuit with many hundreds of pins.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Pin grid arrays and dual-in-line surface mount (SOIC) packages were being produced with more and more pins, and with decreasing spacing between the pins, but this was causing difficulties for the soldering process.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] As package pins got closer together, the danger of accidentally bridging adjacent pins with solder grew.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] A further advantage of BGA packages over packages with discrete leads (i.e. packages with legs) is the lower thermal resistance between the package and the PCB.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] This allows heat generated by the integrated circuit inside the package to flow more easily to the PCB, preventing the chip from overheating.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] The shorter an electrical conductor, the lower its unwanted inductance, a property which causes unwanted distortion of signals in high-speed electronic circuits.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] BGAs, with their very short distance between the package and the PCB, have low lead inductances, giving them superior electrical performance over pinned devices.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] A disadvantage of BGAs is that the solder balls cannot flex in the way that longer leads can, so they are not mechanically compliant.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] As with all surface mount devices, bending due to a difference in coefficient of thermal expansion between PCB substrate and BGA (thermal stress) or flexing and vibration (mechanical stress) can cause the solder joints to fracture.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Thermal expansion issues can be overcome by matching the mechanical and thermal characteristics of the PCB to those of the package.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Typically, plastic BGA devices more closely match PCB thermal characteristics than ceramic devices.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Mechanical stress issues can be overcome by bonding the devices to the board through a process called "underfilling", which injects an epoxy mixture under the device after it is soldered to the PCB, effectively gluing the BGA device to the PCB.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] There are several types of underfill materials in use with differing properties relative to workability and thermal transfer.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] An additional advantage of underfill is that it limits tin whisker growth.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Another solution to non-compliant connections is to put a "compliant layer" in the package that allows the balls to physically move in relation to the package.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] This technique has become standard for packaging DRAMs in BGA packages.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Other techniques for increasing the board-level reliability of packages include use of low-expansion PCBs for ceramic BGA (CBGA) packages, interposers between the package and PCB, and re-packaging a device.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Once the package is soldered into place, it is difficult to find soldering faults.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] X-ray machines, industrial CT scanning machines, special microscopes, and endoscopes to look underneath the soldered package have been developed to overcome this problem.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] If a BGA is found to be badly soldered, it can be removed in a *rework station*, which is a jig fitted with infrared lamp (or hot air), a thermocouple and a vacuum device for lifting the package.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] The BGA can be replaced with a new one, or it can be refurbished (or *reballed*) and re-installed on the circuit board.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Pre-configured solder balls matching the array pattern can be used to reball BGAs when only one or a few need to be reworked.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] For higher volume and repeated lab work, a stencil-configured vacuum-head pick-up and placement of loose spheres can be used.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Due to the cost of visual X-ray BGA inspection, electrical testing is very often used instead.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Very common is boundary scan testing using an IEEE 1149.1 JTAG port.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] A cheaper and easier inspection method, albeit destructive, is becoming increasingly popular because it does not require special equipment.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Commonly referred to as dye and pry, the process includes immersing the entire PCB or just the BGA attached module into a dye, and after drying, the module is pried off and the broken joins are inspected.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] If a solder location contains the dye, then it indicates that the connection was imperfect.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] During development it is not practical to solder BGAs into place, and sockets are used instead, but tend to be unreliable.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] There are two common types of socket: the more reliable type has spring pins that push up under the balls, although it does not allow using BGAs with the balls removed as the spring pins may be too short.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] The less reliable type is a ZIF socket, with spring pinchers that grab the balls.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] This does not work well, especially if the balls are small.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Expensive equipment is required to reliably solder BGA packages; hand-soldering BGA packages is very difficult and unreliable, usable only for the smallest packages in the smallest quantities.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] However, as more ICs have become available only in leadless (e.g. quad-flat no-leads package) or BGA packages, various DIY reflow methods have been developed using inexpensive heat sources such as heat guns, and domestic toaster ovens and electric skillets.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Effectively also the flip chip methods for mounting chip dies to a carrier is sort of a BGA design derivate with the functional equivalent of the balls there being called bumps or micro bumps.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] This is realized at an already microscopic size level.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] To make it easier to use ball grid array devices, most BGA packages only have balls in the outer rings of the package, leaving the innermost square empty.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Intel used a package designated BGA1 for their Pentium II and early Celeron mobile processors.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] BGA2 is Intel's package for their Pentium III and some later Celeron mobile processors.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] For example, the "micro-FCBGA" (flip chip ball grid array) is Intel's current BGA mounting method for mobile processors that use a flip chip binding technology.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] It was introduced with the *Coppermine* Mobile Celeron.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Micro-FCBGA has 479 balls that are 0.78 mm in diameter.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] The processor is affixed to the motherboard by soldering the balls to the motherboard.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] This is thinner than a pin grid array socket arrangement, but is not removable.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] The 479 balls of the Micro-FCBGA package (a package almost identical to the 478-pin socketable micro-FCPGA package) are arranged as the 6 outer rings of a 1.27 mm pitch (20 balls per inch pitch) 26x26 square grid, with the inner 14x14 region empty.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] Primary end-users of BGAs are original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] There is also a market among electronic hobbyists do it yourself (DIY) such as the increasingly popular maker movement.
[src:system-in-package/ball-grid-array] While OEMs generally source their components from the manufacturer, or the manufacturer's distributor, the hobbyist will typically obtain BGAs on the aftermarket through electronic component brokers or distributors.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Pads are metallized on the surface of the chips.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Chips are flipped and positioned so that the solder balls are facing the connectors on the external circuitry.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Solder balls are then remelted (typically using hot air reflow).
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Mounted chip is "underfilled" using a (capillary, shown here) electrically-insulating adhesive.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] In typical semiconductor fabrication systems, chips are built up in large numbers on a single large wafer of semiconductor material, typically silicon.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The individual chips are patterned with small pads of metal near their edges that serve as the connections to an eventual mechanical carrier.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The chips are then cut out of the wafer and attached to their carriers, typically via wire bonding such as thermosonic bonding.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] These wires eventually lead to pins on the outside of the carriers, which are attached to the rest of the circuitry making up the electronic system.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Processing a flip chip is similar to conventional IC fabrication, with a few additional steps.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Near the end of the manufacturing process, the attachment pads are metalized to make them more receptive to solder.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] This typically consists of several treatments.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] A small dot of solder is then deposited on each metalized pad.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The chips are then cut out of the wafer as normal.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] To attach the flip chip into a circuit, the chip is inverted to bring the solder dots down onto connectors or pads on the underlying electronics or circuit board or substrate.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The solder is then re-melted to produce an electrical connection, typically using a thermosonic bonding or alternatively reflow solder process.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] This also leaves a small space between the chip's circuitry and the underlying mounting.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] In many cases an electrically-insulating adhesive is then "underfilled" to provide a stronger mechanical connection, provide a heat bridge, and to ensure the solder joints are not stressed due to differential heating of the chip and the rest of the system.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The underfill distributes the thermal expansion mismatch between the chip and the board, preventing stress concentration in the solder joints which would lead to premature failure.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] This allows the solder to adhere to the contact pads of the chips during the electroplating process.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The seed metals are alloys and are deposited by sputtering onto the wafer with the chips to be bumped.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] A photoresist mask is used to only deposit the seed metal on top of the contact pads of the chips.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The wafer then undergoes electroplating, and the photoresist layer is removed or stripped.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Then the solder on the chips undergoes solder reflow to form the bumps into their final shape.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Solder balls are often 75 to 500 microns in diameter.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] In 2008, High-speed mounting methods evolved through a cooperation between Reel Service Ltd. and Siemens in the development of a high speed mounting tape known as 'MicroTape'[1].
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] By adding a tape-and-reel process into the assembly methodology, placement at high speed is possible, achieving a 99.90% pick rate and a placement rate of 21,000 cph (components per hour), using standard PCB assembly equipment.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Flip-chip packages often consist of a silicon die sitting on top of a "substrate" which then sits on top of a traditional PCB.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The substrate can have a Ball Grid Array (BGA) on its underside.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The substrate makes the connections to the die available for use by the PCB.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Substates made with build up film such as Ajinomoto Build up Film (ABF), are manufactured around a core, and the film is stacked on the core in layers by vacuum lamination at high temperatures.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Tape-automated bonding (TAB) was developed for connecting dies with thermocompression or thermosonic bonding to a flexible substrate including from one to three conductive layers.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Also with TAB it is possible to connect die pins all at the same time as with the soldering based flip-chip mounting.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The resulting completed flip-chip assembly is much smaller than a traditional carrier-based system; the chip sits directly on the circuit board, and is much smaller than the carrier both in area and height.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The short wires greatly reduce inductance, allowing higher-speed signals, and also conduct heat better.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The lack of a carrier means they are not suitable for easy replacement, or unaided manual installation.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] They also require very flat mounting surfaces, which is not always easy to arrange, or sometimes difficult to maintain as the boards heat and cool.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Also, the short connections are very stiff, so the thermal expansion of the chip must be matched to the supporting board or the connections can crack.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The underfill material acts as an intermediate between the difference in CTE of the chip and board.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] The process was originally introduced commercially by IBM in the 1960s for individual transistors and diodes packaged for use in their mainframe systems.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Ceramic substrates for flip-chip BGA were replaced with organic substrates to reduce costs and use existing PCB manufacturing techniques to produce more packages at a time by using larger PCB panels during manufacturing.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Ajinomoto Build up Film (ABF) was developed in 1999 and has become a material widely used in flip-chip packages, used for manufacturing flip-chip substrates in a semi-additive process, first pioneered by Intel.
[src:system-in-package/flip-chip] Build up film helped transition the industry away from ceramic substrates, and this film is now essential in the production of organic flip-chip package substrates.
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] Other terms for MCM packaging include "heterogeneous integration" or "hybrid integrated circuit".
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] The advantage of using MCM packaging is it allows a manufacturer to use multiple components for modularity and/or to improve yields over a conventional monolithic IC approach.
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] A **Flip Chip Multi-Chip Module** (**FCMCM**) is a multi-chip module that uses flip chip technology.
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] A FCMCM may have one large die and several smaller dice all on the same module.
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] Multi-chip modules come in a variety of forms depending on the complexity and development philosophies of their designers.
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] These can range from using pre-packaged ICs on a small printed circuit board (PCB) meant to mimic the package footprint of an existing chip package to fully custom chip packages integrating many chip dies on a high density interconnection (HDI) substrate.
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] This is often either organic (a laminated circuit board that contains carbon, hence *organic*) or is made of silicon (as in High Bandwidth Memory).
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] Using interposers to connect several ICs instead of connecting several monolithic ICs in separate packages reduces the power needed to transmit signals between ICs, increases the number of transmission channels, and reduces delays caused by resistance and capacitance (RC delays).
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] However, communication between chiplets consumes more power and has higher latency than components within monolithic ICs.
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] A relatively new development in MCM technology is the so-called "chip-stack" package.
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] Certain ICs, memories in particular, have very similar or identical pinouts when used multiple times within systems.
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] A carefully designed substrate can allow these dies to be stacked in a vertical configuration making the resultant MCM's footprint much smaller (albeit at the cost of a thicker or taller chip).
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] Since area is more often at a premium in miniature electronics designs, the chip-stack is an attractive option in many applications such as cell phones and personal digital assistants (PDAs).
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] With the use of a 3D integrated circuit and a thinning process, as many as ten dies can be stacked to create a high capacity SD memory card.
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] This technique can also be used for High Bandwidth Memory.
[src:system-in-package/multi-chip-module] The possible way to increasing the performance of data transfer in the Chip stack is use Wireless Networks on Chip (WiNoC).
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] A **system in a package**, or **system in package** (**SiP**), is a number of integrated circuits (ICs) enclosed in one chip carrier package or encompassing an IC package substrate that may include passive components and perform the functions of an entire system.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] The ICs may be stacked using die stacking or package on package, placed side by side (multi-chip module, MCM), and/or embedded in the substrate.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] The SiP performs all or most of the functions of an electronic system, and is typically used when designing components for mobile phones, digital music players, etc.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] Dies containing integrated circuits may be stacked vertically on the package substrate.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] They are internally connected by fine wires that are bonded to the package substrate.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] Alternatively, with a flip chip technology, solder bumps are used to join stacked chips together and to the package substrate, or even both techniques can be used in a single package.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] SiPs are like systems on a chip (SoCs) but less tightly integrated and not on a single semiconductor die.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] SIPs can be used either to reduce the size of a system, improve performance or to reduce costs.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] Some definitions of SiP exclude those that only use two-dimensional MCM.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] SiP dies can be stacked vertically or tiled horizontally, with techniques like chiplets or quilt packaging.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] SiPs connect the dies with standard off-chip wire bonds or solder bumps, unlike slightly denser three-dimensional integrated circuits which connect stacked silicon dies with conductors running through the die using through-silicon vias.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] Many different 3D packaging techniques have been developed for stacking many fairly standard chip dies into a compact area.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] SiPs can contain several chips or dies—such as a specialized processor, DRAM, flash memory—combined with passive components—resistors and capacitors—all mounted on the same substrate.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] This means that a complete functional unit can be built in a single package, so that few external components need to be added to make it work.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] This is particularly valuable in space constrained environments like MP3 players and mobile phones as it reduces the complexity of the printed circuit board and overall design.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] Despite its benefits, this technique decreases the yield of fabrication since any defective chip in the package will result in a non-functional packaged integrated circuit, even if all other modules in that same package are functional.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] SiPs are in contrast to the common system on a chip (SoC) integrated circuit architecture which integrates components based on function into a single circuit die.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] An SoC will typically integrate a CPU, graphics and memory interfaces, hard-disk and USB connectivity, random-access and read-only memories, and secondary storage and/or their controllers on a single die.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] In comparison a SiP would connect these modules as discrete components in one or more chip packages or dies.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] A SiP resembles the common traditional motherboard-based PC architecture, as it separates components based on function and connects them through a central interfacing circuit board.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] A SiP has a lower grade of integration in comparison to an SoC.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] SiP solutions may require multiple packaging technologies, such as flip chip, wire bonding, wafer-level packaging, through-silicon vias (TSVs), chiplets and more.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] SiP technology is primarily being driven by early market trends in wearables, mobile devices and the Internet of things which do not demand the high numbers of produced units as in the established consumer and business SoC market.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] As the Internet of things becomes more commonplace in the SiP market, advances in SiP packaging design enable microelectromechanical (MEMS) sensors to be integrated on a separate die and control connectivity.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] Desktop SiPs generally integrate CPU, memory controller, high-speed IO (PCIe/USB3/USB4), and sometimes integrated graphics.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] Storage such as main memory and disks are left separate.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] AMD desktop CPUs since Zen 2 use a MCM design.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] The CPU handles its own PCIe, USB3, and in those with integrated graphics, display output.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] Lower-speed I/O such as extra PCIe lanes, SATA, slower USB, and serial links such as SPI and SMBus are still handled by a "chipset", actually a PCIe device.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] Intel mobile CPUs beginning with ultra-low-power Haswells and continuing with mobile Skylake also use a SiP design.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] These directly expose PCIe lanes, as well as SATA, USB, and HDA lines from integrated controllers, and SPI/I²C/UART/GPIO lines for sensors.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] Like PCH-compatible CPUs, they continue to expose DisplayPort, RAM, and SMBus lines.
[src:system-in-package/system-in-package] However, a fully integrated voltage regulator will be absent until Cannon Lake.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] WLP is essentially a true chip-scale package (CSP) technology, since the resulting package is practically of the same size as the die.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] Wafer-level packaging allows integration of wafer fab, packaging, test, and burn-in at wafer level in order to streamline the manufacturing process undergone by a device from silicon start to customer shipment.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] As of 2009, there is no single industry-standard method of wafer-level packaging.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] A major application area of WLPs is their use in smartphones due to the size constraints.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] For example, the Apple iPhone 5 has at least eleven different WLPs, the Samsung Galaxy S3 has six WLPs and the HTC One X has seven.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] Functions provided WLPs in smartphones include sensors, power management, and wireless.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] The iPhone 7 was rumored to use fan-out wafer-level packaging technology in order to achieve a thinner and lighter model.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] Wafer-level chip scale packaging (WL-CSP) is the smallest package currently available on the market and is produced by OSAT (Outsourced Semiconductor Assembly and Test) companies, such as Advanced Semiconductor Engineering (ASE).
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] A WL-CSP or WLCSP package is just a bare die with a redistribution layer (RDL, interposer or I/O pitch) to rearrange the pins or contacts on the die so that they can be big enough and have sufficient spacing so that they can be handled just like a ball grid array (BGA) package.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] The RDL is often made out of a polyamide or polybenzoxazole with copper plated on its surface.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] There are two kinds of wafer level packaging: fan-in and fan-out.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] This is also true in fan-in WLSCP packages.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] In both cases, the die with its interposer may be covered in encapsulating material such as epoxy.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] Fan-out packages are used in cases where fan-in packages are not able to provide enough connections at a specified cost.
[src:system-in-package/wafer-level-packaging] In February 2015, it was discovered that a WL-CSP chip in the Raspberry Pi 2 had issues with xenon flashes (or any other bright flashes of longwave light), inducing the photoelectric effect within the chip.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Wire diameters start from under 10 μm and can be up to several hundred micrometres for high-powered applications.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] The wire bonding industry is transitioning from gold to copper.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] This change has been instigated by the rising cost of gold and the comparatively stable, and much lower, cost of copper.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] While possessing higher thermal and electrical conductivity than gold, copper had previously been seen as less reliable due to its hardness and susceptibility to corrosion.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] By 2015, it is expected that more than a third of all wire bonding machines in use will be set up for copper.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Copper wire up to 500 micrometers (0.02 in) can be successfully wedge bonded.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Large diameter copper wire can and does replace aluminium wire where high current carrying capacity is needed or where there are problems with complex geometry.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Annealing and process steps used by manufacturers enhance the ability to use large diameter copper wire to wedge bond to silicon without damage occurring to the die.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Copper wire does pose some challenges in that it is harder than both gold and aluminium, so bonding parameters must be kept under tight control.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] The amount of power used during ultrasonic bonding must be higher and copper has a higher fusing current so it has a higher current carrying capacity.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] The formation of oxides is inherent with this material, so storage and shelf life are issues that must be considered.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Special packaging is required in order to protect copper wire and achieve a longer shelf life.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Palladium coated copper wire is a common alternative which has shown significant resistance to corrosion, albeit at a higher hardness than pure copper and a greater price, though still less than gold.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] During the fabrication of wire bonds, copper wire, as well as its plated varieties, must be worked in the presence of forming gas [95% nitrogen and 5% hydrogen] or a similar anoxic gas in order to prevent corrosion.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] A method for coping with copper's relative hardness is the use of high purity [5N+] varieties.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Long-term corrosion effects (Cu2Si) and other stability topics led to increased quality requirements when used in automotive applications.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Junction size, bond strength and conductivity requirements typically determine the most suitable wire size for a specific wire bonding application.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Typical manufacturers make gold wire in diameters from 8 micrometers (0.00031 in) and larger.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Production tolerance on gold wire diameter is +/-3%.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] All-aluminium systems in semiconductor fabrication eliminate the "purple plague" (brittle gold–aluminium intermetallic compound) sometimes associated with pure gold bonding wire.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Aluminium is particularly suitable for thermosonic bonding.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] In order to assure that high quality bonds can be obtained at high production speeds, special controls are used in the manufacture of 1% silicon–aluminium wire.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] One of the most important characteristics of high grade bonding wire of this type is homogeneity of the alloy system.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Homogeneity is given special attention during the manufacturing process.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Microscopic checks of the alloy structure of finished lots of 1% silicon–aluminium wire are performed routinely.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Processing also is carried out under conditions which yield the ultimate in surface cleanliness and smooth finish and permits entirely snag-free de-reeling.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Ball bonding usually is restricted to gold and copper wire and usually requires heat.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] For wedge bonding, only gold wire requires heat.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Wedge bonding can use large diameter wires or wire ribbons for power electronics application.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Ball bonding is limited to small diameter wires, suitable for interconnect application.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] In either type of wire bonding, the wire is attached at both ends using a combination of downward pressure, ultrasonic energy, and in some cases heat, to make a weld.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] The correct combination of temperature and ultrasonic energy is used in order to maximize the reliability and strength of a wire bond.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] If heat and ultrasonic energy is used, the process is called thermosonic bonding.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] In wedge bonding, the wire must be drawn in a straight line according to the first bond.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] This slows down the process due to time needed for tool alignment.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Ball bonding, however, creates its first bond in a ball shape with the wire sticking out at the top, having no directional preference.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Thus, the wire can be drawn in any direction, making it a faster process.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Compliant bonding transmits heat and pressure through a compliant or indentable aluminium tape and therefore is applicable in bonding gold wires and the beam leads that have been electroformed to the silicon integrated circuit (known as the beam leaded integrated circuit).
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] There are multiple challenges when it comes to wire bond manufacturing and reliability.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] These challenges tend of be a function of several parameters such as the material systems, bonding parameters, and use environment.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Different wire bond–bond pad metal systems such as aluminium–aluminium (Al-Al), gold–aluminium (Au-Al), and copper–aluminium (Cu-Al) require different manufacturing parameters and behave differently under the same use environments.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Much work has been done to characterize various metal systems, review critical manufacturing parameters, and identify typical reliability issues that occur in wire bonding.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] When it comes to material selection, the application and use environment will dictate the metal system.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Often the electrical properties, mechanical properties, and cost are taken into account when making a decision.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] For example, a high current device for a space application might require a large diameter aluminium wire bond in a hermetically sealed ceramic package.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] If cost is a large constraint, then avoiding gold wire bonds may be a necessity.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Some recent work has been done to look at copper wire bonds in automotive applications.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] This is only a small sampling, as there is a vast body of work reviewing and testing what material systems work best in different applications.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] From a manufacturing perspective, the bonding parameters play a critical role in bond formation and bond quality.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Parameters such bond force, ultrasonic energy, temperature, and loop geometry, to name a few, can have a significant effect on bond quality.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] There are various wire bonding techniques (thermosonic bonding, ultrasonic bonding, thermocompression bonding) and types of wire bonds (ball bonding, wedge bonding) that affect susceptibility to manufacturing defects and reliability issues.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Certain materials and wire diameters are more practical for fine pitch or complex layouts.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] The bond pad also plays an important role as the metallization and barrier layer(s) stackup will impact the bond formation.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Typical failure modes that result from poor bond quality and manufacturing defects include: fracture at the ball bond neck, heel cracking (wedge bonds), pad liftoff, pad peel, overcompression, and improper intermetallic formation.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] A combination of wire bond pull/shear testing, nondestructive testing, and destructive physical analysis (DPA) can be used to screen manufacturing and quality issues.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] While wirebond manufacturing tends to focus on bond quality, it often does not account for wearout mechanisms related to wire bond reliability.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] In this case, an understanding of the application and use environment can help prevent reliability issues.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Common examples of environments that lead to wire bond failures include elevated temperature, humidity, and temperature cycling.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Under elevated temperatures, excessive intermetallics (IMC) growth can create brittle points of fracture.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Much work that has been done to characterize the intermetallic formation and aging for various metal systems.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] This not a problem in metal systems where the wire bond and bond pad are the same material such as Al-Al.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] This does become a concern in dissimilar metal systems.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] One of the most well known examples is the brittle intermetallics formed in gold–aluminium IMCs such as purple plague.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Additionally, diffusion related issues, such as Kirkendall voiding and Horsting voiding, can also lead to wire bond failures.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Under elevated temperature and humidity environments, corrosion can be a concern.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] This is most common in Au-Al metal systems and is driven by galvanic corrosion.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] The presence of halides such as chlorine can accelerate this behavior.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] This Au-Al corrosion is often characterized with Peck's law for temperature and humidity.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] This is not as common in other metal systems.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Under temperature cycling, thermomechanical stress is generated in the wire bond as a result of coefficient of thermal expansion (CTE) mismatch between the epoxy molding compound (EMC), the leadframe, the die, the die adhesive, and the wire bond.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] This leads to low cycle fatigue due to shear or tensile stresses in the wire bond.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Various fatigue models have been used to predict the fatigue life of wire bonds under such conditions, such as Paris' law.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Fatigue models can be coupled with data-driven approaches, such as physics-informed Markov chains, to account for uncertainty and to better generalize for predictions on lower temperature.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Proper understanding of the use environment and metal systems are often the most important factors for increasing wire bond reliability.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] While there are some wire bond pull and shear testing techniques such as MIL-STD-883, ASTM F459-13, and JESD22-B116, these tend to be applicable for manufacturing quality rather than reliability.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] They are often monotonic overstress techniques, where peak force and fracture location are the critical outputs.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] In this case the damage is plasticity dominated, and does not reflect some wearout mechanisms that might be seen under environmental conditions.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Wire pull testing applies an upward force under the wire, effectively pulling it away from the substrate or die.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] The purpose of the test is as MIL-STD-883 2011.9 describes it: "To measure bond strengths, evaluate bond strength distributions, or determine compliance with specified bond strength requirements".
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] A wire can be pulled to destruction, but there are also non-destructive variants whereby one tests whether the wire can withstand a certain force.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Non-destructive test methods are typically used for 100% testing of safety critical, high quality and high cost products, avoiding damage to the acceptable wired bonds tested.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] The term wire pull usually refers to the act of pulling a wire with a hook mounted on a pull sensor on a bond tester.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] However, to promote certain failure modes, wires can be cut and then pulled by tweezers, also mounted on a pull sensor on a bond tester.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Usually wires up to 75 μm diameter (3 mil) are classified as thin wire.
[src:system-in-package/wire-bonding] Beyond that size, we speak about thick wire testing.
